SECTION 1 — Ecosystem Stability: Definition & Importance
The capacity of an ecosystem to maintain its structure and function
1.1 What is Ecosystem Stability?
Ecosystem stability is the capacity of an ecosystem to maintain its structure (species composition, food
web) and function (energy flow, nutrient cycling, productivity) in the face of disturbances, and to recover
when disturbed. It is an emergent property — it arises from the interactions among all components of the
ecosystem.
Why stability matters: A stable ecosystem provides continuous ecosystem services (food, water,
climate regulation, etc.) on which human civilisation depends. Unstable ecosystems collapse,
losing these services permanently.
1.2 Key Definitions
n Perturbation / Disturbance:
Any event that disrupts the ecosystem structure, function, or composition. Can be natural (fire, flood,
drought, storm, volcanic eruption) or anthropogenic (pollution, deforestation, overgrazing, invasive
species).
n Equilibrium:
A state in which ecosystem properties (species composition, biomass, nutrient levels) remain relatively
constant over time. Can be stable equilibrium (returns after disturbance) or unstable equilibrium.
n Homeostasis:
The ability of an ecosystem to self-regulate and return to a stable state after a small disturbance —
through negative feedback mechanisms.
n Regime Shift:
A sudden, dramatic change in an ecosystem from one stable state to another, triggered when a tipping
point is crossed. Often irreversible.
