Resistance Definition: The ability of an ecosystem to resist displacement — to stay the same
when subjected to a disturbance. A highly resistant ecosystem does not change
much when disturbed. Analogy: A deep cup — the ball (ecosystem) stays put even
when pushed. Related to: Inertia, robustness Examples: • Tropical rainforest —
extremely resistant to moderate disturbances due to high biodiversity • Old-growth
forests with complex structure resist wind damage better than plantations • Coral
reefs with high diversity resist mild bleaching events Higher in: Complex,
species-rich, mature ecosystems
Resilience Definition: The ability of an ecosystem to recover quickly after a disturbance — to
bounce back to its original state. Analogy: A shallow cup — ball gets displaced but
springs back quickly. Types of resilience: • Engineering resilience: how fast it
returns • Ecological resilience: how large a disturbance can be absorbed
Examples: • Grasslands recover quickly after fire (high resilience) • Annual crops
bounce back after pest attacks • Planktonic ecosystems recover rapidly from
pollution Higher in: Simpler, early-successional, productive ecosystems
