Fig 3: Factors Affecting Ecosystem Stability — Mind Map
1. Species Diversity MORE species = MORE stability (generally). Higher biodiversity provides
functional redundancy — if one species is lost, another can fill its role. This is
the diversity-stability hypothesis. Evidence: David Tilman's grassland
experiments (1994) showed that plots with more plant species were more
resistant to drought and more productive. Exception: Some simple
ecosystems (e.g., grasslands) are MORE resilient than complex ones — the
relationship is not always linear.
2. Food Web Complexity More connections in food web = more stable ecosystem. Complex food
webs provide alternative energy pathways — if one path is disrupted, energy
can flow through another. Robert May (1972) challenged this with
mathematical models showing that complexity can destabilise if too high
(May's paradox). MacArthur (1955) proposed complexity-stability hypothesis
originally. Current view: moderate complexity with functional redundancy =
optimal stability.
