3. Keystone Species
Presence
Keystone species have disproportionately large effects on ecosystem
structure. Their presence/absence dramatically affects stability. Example:
Sea otter (Enhydra lutris) — controls sea urchin populations which protects
kelp forests. Without otters ® urchin explosion ® kelp forest collapse.
Top-down control by apex predators stabilises ecosystems (trophic
cascades).
4. Disturbance Regime Intermediate Disturbance Hypothesis (Connell, 1978): Intermediate
frequency/intensity disturbances maintain highest diversity, which supports
stability. • Low disturbance ® competitive exclusion ® low diversity ® less
stable • High disturbance ® only tolerant species survive ® less stable •
Intermediate ® many species coexist ® more stable Regular disturbances
(fire in grasslands, floods in riparian zones) are often ESSENTIAL for
long-term stability.
5. Functional
Redundancy
When multiple species perform the same ecological function (pollinators,
decomposers, nitrogen fixers), the loss of one species does NOT cause
function collapse — others compensate. Analogy: Like having backup
electrical circuits — if one fails, others operate. HIGH functional redundancy
® HIGH stability. Low redundancy (single-species functions) ® FRAGILE
ecosystem.
6. Physical Environment
Stability
Stable physical conditions (consistent temperature, rainfall, nutrient levels)
support stable biological communities. • Stable environments ® specialist
species ® high diversity ® high resistance • Variable environments ®
generalist species ® lower diversity but high resilience Climate change is
destabilising previously stable physical environments, threatening ecosystem
stability globally.
