Charles Elton (1958) In "The Ecology of Invasions by Animals and Plants," Elton argued that
simple ecosystems are more vulnerable to invasion than complex ones.
Monocultures are fragile; diverse natural communities resist invaders better.
This was an early statement of the diversity-stability hypothesis.
Robert MacArthur (1955) Proposed the complexity-stability hypothesis: more complex food webs
(more species, more connections) lead to more stable ecosystems. Stability
measured by evenness of energy flow — more pathways = more stability.
Robert May (1972) Using mathematical models, May showed that complexity can actually
DESTABILISE ecosystems — contradicting MacArthur. This is "May's
Paradox": why are real complex ecosystems stable despite theory? Answer:
real food webs have non-random structure (compartments, weak links) that
maintains stability.
David Tilman (1994) Landmark grassland biodiversity experiments at Cedar Creek (Minnesota).
Found that plots with MORE plant species were: (1) More resistant to drought
(2) More productive (higher biomass) (3) More efficient at using nutrients
Strong empirical evidence for diversity-stability hypothesis.
