SECTION 6 — Keystone Species and Stability
Species with disproportionately large effects on ecosystem stability
6.1 What is a Keystone Species?
A keystone species is a species whose effect on its community or ecosystem is disproportionately large
relative to its abundance. Removing a keystone species causes dramatic changes in the ecosystem —
often collapse. Term coined by Robert Paine (1969) based on starfish removal experiments.
Analogy: Just like the keystone in an arch — a small central stone that holds the entire arch together.
Remove it and the whole arch collapses.
Sea Otter (Enhydra
lutris)
Classic keystone predator. Controls sea urchin populations on Pacific coast.
Without otters ® urchins explode ® overgraze kelp ® kelp forest disappears ®
loss of shelter for hundreds of species. WITH otters ® healthy kelp forest. Studied
by Paine and Estes in Pacific coast.
African Elephant Ecosystem engineer and keystone species in African savanna. Elephants push
over trees, creating open grassland habitat for grazers. Dig waterholes that other
species use. Disperse seeds over large distances. Without elephants ® bush
encroachment ® grassland species decline.
Fig Trees (Ficus
species)
Keystone PLANT species in tropical forests. Fig trees produce fruit year-round
(when other trees do not), supporting frugivores (fruit bats, birds, primates) during
food scarcity. Called "survival foods" — without them, many tropical vertebrates
would go extinct.
Wolves (Canis
lupus)
Classic trophic cascade example — Yellowstone National Park. Wolves
reintroduced in 1995 ® reduced deer/elk grazing ® vegetation recovered ®
riverbanks stabilised ® rivers changed course. "How wolves change rivers" —
famous trophic cascade.
Sharks Apex predators in marine ecosystems. Control prey populations, maintaining
trophic structure. Removing sharks ® prey explosion ® overgrazing of seagrass
beds and algae ® coastal ecosystem collapse.
Bees & Pollinators Keystone MUTUALISTS. ~80% of flowering plants depend on animal pollination.
Decline of bees threatens food security and ecosystem function. Worth ~$577
billion/year in global crop production.
6.2 Trophic Cascade
A trophic cascade occurs when a top predator controls herbivore populations, which in turn allows
vegetation to thrive — a "top-down" effect flowing down through the food chain. Removing the top predator
triggers a cascade of changes down to the producers.
