SECTION 14 — Threats to Ecosystem Stability & Services
What is destabilising the world's ecosystems
Habitat Loss &
Fragmentation
Largest threat to ecosystem stability. Deforestation, wetland drainage, urban
sprawl reduce ecosystem size and connectivity. India: 35% forest cover lost;
80% of wetlands degraded. Fragmentation isolates populations ® reduced
genetic diversity ® lower resilience.
Invasive Alien
Species
Species introduced outside their native range disrupt established food webs,
outcompete native species, alter ecosystem processes. Examples: Lantana
camara in Indian forests; Water hyacinth in Indian lakes; Parthenium (Congress
grass) in Indian grasslands.
Overexploitation Unsustainable harvesting of species (hunting, fishing, logging) removes
keystone species and disrupts trophic structure. Examples: Overfishing
collapsing marine food webs; Poaching removing tigers (keystone predators).
Pollution Chemical pollution (pesticides, heavy metals, plastics) kills species and disrupts
ecosystem processes. Eutrophication (excess N, P) triggers tipping points in
aquatic ecosystems. Air pollution damages forests, reduces pollinator
populations.
Climate Change Alters temperature, precipitation, seasonality — disrupts species ranges,
phenology, and ecosystem processes. Pushes ecosystems past tipping points.
Coral bleaching; Arctic sea ice loss; Himalayan glacier retreat; Amazon die-back
risk.
Overgrazing & Land
Degradation
Excessive livestock grazing removes vegetation, compacts soil, initiates
desertification — crossing tipping points to degraded state. India: 120 million
hectares of degraded land (ICAR 2019).
