Ecosystem engineer Species that physically modifies the environment, creating/maintaining habitat for
others.
Ecosystem services Benefits humans obtain from ecosystems — provisioning, regulating, cultural,
supporting.
Elasticity Speed of return to equilibrium after disturbance (Pimm, 1984). = Engineering
resilience.
Functional redundancy Multiple species performing same ecological function — provides stability buffer.
Homeostasis Ecosystem's ability to self-regulate and return to stable state through negative
feedback.
Hysteresis Recovery pathway differs from degradation pathway — makes ecosystem restoration
difficult.
Keystone species Species with disproportionately large ecosystem effect relative to abundance (Paine,
1969).
MEA 2005 Millennium Ecosystem Assessment — UN study classifying ecosystem services into 4
categories.
Paine (1969) Coined "keystone species" based on Pisaster sea star removal experiments.
Persistence Ability of ecosystem to continue existing over long time periods.
Regime shift Sudden change from one stable ecosystem state to another; triggered by crossing
tipping point.
Resilience Ability of ecosystem to recover after disturbance (bounce back).
Resistance Ability of ecosystem to resist displacement when disturbed (stay the same).
Robustness Ability to maintain function under diverse/novel conditions.
Tipping point Threshold beyond which small change triggers sudden, large, often irreversible
ecosystem change.
Tilman (1994) Cedar Creek experiments proving more plant diversity ® higher stability and
productivity.
